$$, $$46b1a8e4343feaa47977d7204d85afef4522968c294b381e0cf8488b7ccaba8c$$, $${"A": "c6250f589e50ba006fec20d8e13eff70a617e73677c82117657197dbdd7826d9", "C": "52ad033b4f943517ccc7201355e27d957c9ff241d5a45f03b26bcbce1997c1d8", "D": "1bb3e1506bed2c27eab0e98cf6aeffe6703cd2ef42af67f90450b93ba8b5820c"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Army/RDTE - Vol 2 - Budget Activity 4B.pdf$$, 271, $$2026-05-07T23:10:23.471687+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0603160BR$$, 2027, $$Defense Threat Reduction Agency's (DTRA's) Counter Weapons of Mass Destruction (WMD) Advanced Technology Development (ATD) Program capitalizes on Applied
Research (Budget Activity 6.2) RDT&E transitioning to the development of advanced concepts, components, and prototypes.
The project objective is to determine technical feasibility and practicality of a new technologies and approaches to solve WMD problems and integrate components and
subsystems into system prototypes for testing in realistic or simulated environments.
DTRA’s RDT&E WMD project accomplishes these objectives through four project areas.
The CWMD Cross-Cutting Technical and Information Sciences project develops concepts and technologies in the areas of high-speed information processing, modeling
and simulation, signal detection, and data-driven decision analysis in support of the DTRA's technical teams.
The Nuclear Technologies and Capabilities Development project develops direct and indirect technologies for the detection of radiation and nonradioactive signatures
associated with nuclear threats, and advance warfighter capabilities to rapidly locate, characterize, and counter such threats.
The CWMD Technologies and Capabilities Development project develops innovative kinetic and non-kinetic weapons technologies to expand traditional and asymmetric
options available to Combatant Commanders to deny, disrupt, and defeat adversarial use of WMD while minimizing collateral effects.
The CWMD Test and Evaluation project provides unique national test bed capability for the study of weapon-target interaction, simulated WMD facility characterization,
and WMD facility defeat testing to evaluate the implications of WMD and other special weapon use against U.S. military and civilian assets.
DTRA will conduct Research & Development (R&D) to address adversary Hardened and Deeply Buried Target (HDBT) threats and capabilities as outlined in the
National Defense Strategy (NDS), Defense Planning Guidance (DPG), and supporting Combatant Command operational requirements.
DTRA will lead HDBT-Defeat requirement development and capability planning, coordination, and prioritization in support of a larger, collaborative HDBT-Defeat
capability development strategy in concert with DoW and Combatant Command strategies and priorities. DTRA will advocate for Service HDBT-Defeat capabilities and
programs in accordance with applicable strategies, plans, and guidance.$$, $$The Countering Weapons of Mass Destruction (CWMD) Test and Evaluation project provides a unique national test capability for simulated Weapons of Mass
Destruction (WMD) facilities and processes. This capability provides DTRA’s structured and systematic end-to-end test event planning, preparation, management,
execution, and data analysis. It also offers test instrumentation (data acquisition systems and optics), scientific analysis and predictions, test article construction, test
article/test bed remediation, tunnel mining, architectural and engineering design, systems engineering and integration, and test data management. The project leverages
50 years of expertise in investigating weapons effects and target response across the spectrum of hostile environments that could be created by proliferative nations or
terrorist organizations with access to advanced conventional weapons or WMD. Subject matter experts design full and sub-scale testing strategies focusing on weapon-
target interaction with fixed soft and hardened facilities to include above ground facilities, cut-and-cover facilities, and deep underground tunnels.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2025           FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: RR: CWMD Test and Evaluation                                                                                                          11.306            11.675      20.726
Description: This project employs technology development, modeling-and-simulation, and analysis support tools to meet
Combatant Command requirements and anticipated threats. DTRA provides timely acquisition and delivery of solutions that
respond to asymmetric threat requirements and gaps.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Sustain a capability to manage two Petabytes of historic test data and 200 Terabytes per year of future data in compliance with
