- Transition novel detection and characterization of adversary mobile systems, technologies enabling novel communications to
underwater defeat systems against adversary subsea infrastructure and pre-deployed underwater systems.
RDT&E efforts to defeat Hardened and Deeply Buried Target (HDBT) may include:
- Improve efforts on penetration analysis, modeling, and testing to more effectively support development of new penetrating
weapons and weaponeering tools for HDBT defeat in a wide variety of geologies.
- Develop breaching charges with integrated blast pressure mitigation for defeat of barriers in hand dug, naturally occurring
spaces, or dense urban environments.
- Accelerate development of the Ring Initiation Focused Fragmentation Charge to increase lethality of ground force with safety
review, production scale up for Operational Test and Evaluation, and Fielding and Deployment.
- Advance multi-domain (space to sea floor) tactical communications technologies for anti-access area denial, and denied area
access for Special Operations Forces and partner nations in U.S. Indo-Pacific Command and other Combatant Commands areas
of responsibility.
- Leverage Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning to improve the ability to quickly weaponeer against a broad range of hard
targets thus freeing Subject Matter Experts (human SMEs) to focus their efforts on the most complex and specialized HDBTs.
- Enhance current weapon multi-hit tactic; determine maximum penetration depth of current weapons; determine the maximum
limit of current weapons against a range of geologies including weak rock/soil utilizing the multi-hit tactic.
- Conduct R&D in “skip” bombing capability to develop new tactics and weaponeering options; enabling deeper access for
penetrating weapons
- Improve targeting and weaponeering against hardened maritime and near shore targets; build and validate both high fidelity and
engineering models to enable weaponeering in the Integrated Munitions Effects Assessment toolset.
- Evaluate current hard target defeat capabilities with 2000lb Joint Direct Attack Munition Extended Range (JDAM-ER) (GBU-64)
and provide recommendations on future JDAM-ER development to enhance HDBT penetration capabilities.
