INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0105519N$$, 2027, $$The Department encourages additional vendor participation in the design, development, and production of alternative weapons systems to meet current and future
warfighting requirements. With current major weapons systems production at capacity, the nation is looking for alternative systems to fill these gaps. The Department is
implementing diverse
procurement strategies to enable rapid acquisition. These will include the use of Other Transaction Authorities, 'Marketplace' acquisition platforms, and alternative
concepts to increase supply and suppliers in addition to traditional FAR-based procurement strategies.

 The FY 2026 spend plan includes $0 thousand of discretionary and $1,677,309 thousand of reconciliation for a total of $1,677,309 thousand.

 The Nuclear-Armed Sea Launched Cruise Missile Program (SLCM-N) is not a new start in FY2027. No discretionary funding is requested for FY2027.

 SLCM-N is a theater nuclear system intended to expand the President's options for responding to limited nuclear use and strategic non-nuclear attacks. SLCM-N
 enables a persistent, survivable regional nuclear presence that provides assurance to U.S. allies of a credible U.S. theater nuclear response, without dependence on
 allied host nations.

 The SLCM-N program was established per the Acquisition Decision Memorandum (ADM) dated March 15, 2024. The ADM designated SLCM-N an ACAT ID Major
 Defense Acquisition Program with the Navy as the lead component, as well as authorized the program's entry into the Materiel Solutions Analysis phase. The SLCM-N
 program is planning to achieve Initial Operational Capability by 30 September 2034 per the FY2024 NDAA and Limited Operational Capability by 30 September 2032
 per the FY2026 NDAA.

 SLCM-N Enterprise System is composed of the SLCM-N Weapon System and Integrated Product Support (IPS). It requires the aggregation of both the Weapon System
 and IPS to produce the required capability of the SLCM-N program. Nuclear Weapon Surety (Safety, Security, and Use Control) applies across the entire SLCM-N
 Enterprise System. The SLCM-N Weapon System is the composition of the flight vehicle, warhead, capsule, canister, fire control, enabling platform equipment, and
 multiple canister launcher that will function onboard a launch platform. SLCM-N IPS addresses respective subsystems and implementation. The scope of IPS includes
 the enterprise level integration aligned to DoDI_5000.91: Facilities and Infrastructure, Support Equipment, Training Activities, Packaging, Handling, Storage, and
 Transportation, and Sustaining Engineering.

 Mandatory funding supports the following SLCM-N program cost categories and corresponding efforts:

 Missile Systems:

 The Missile System consists of:
 All-Up Round (AUR), which includes: 1) Flight Vehicle and 2) Canister
 Multiple Canister Launcher (MCL)Missile System Integrated Product Support Subsystem, which includes: 1) Facilities and Infrastructure; 2) Support Equipment; 3)
 Training Activities and Equipment; and 4) Packaging, Handling, and Storage Equipment.

 The Missile System will be delivered to the VIRGINIA-Class submarine; each AUR, will be loaded into an MCL. The AURs and MCLs will be supported by the Missile
 System Integrated Product Support System, which includes facilities and infrastructure to develop, test, process and deliver the system, all common/unique support
 equipment, procedures, and training curriculum. The Missile System also includes all Shore CONOPS, planning activities and requirement definition for shore integration
 facilities and development of associated program documentation. Activities to be performed with mandatory funding include:
 Complete Phase 1 of competitive design and prototyping contracts for the AUR and MCL and transition to Phase 2 subsystem prototyping testing
 Transition from Phase 1 design and prototyping contracts for the AUR and MCL, to Phase 2 subsystem prototyping testing
 Conduct component testing (Software in the Loop, Hardware in the Loop)
 Procure hardware for developmental testing
 Perform prototyping and ground testing of Missile Subsystem and Launcher Subsystem components
 Perform detailed planning to enable future underwater launch testing and qualification prior to platform integration.
 Assess concept designs for Missile System components
 Develop and build prototype inert AURs and MCLs to support competitive launcher testing
 Develop and build prototype inert AURs and test equipment to support competitive flight testing
 Assess system performance during flight testing and assess final concepts
 Design missile specification and mission load interfaces ensuring validation and verification requirements meet nuclear and cyber security standards
 Conduct payload integration, and interface testing and analysis
 Coordinate with industry partners to ensure specific platform requirements (hardware, software, cybersecurity, system safety, external data sources, launcher, HMI,
 SWAP, etc.) are identified and integrated appropriately
 Initiate component-level testing, initiate launcher interface gas generator and ejector Design Developmental Test and Evaluation
 Conduct MCL/Canister platform interface verification planning
 Begin/launch sequence analysis
 Complete IAL campaign 1 to baseline anticipated launcher and flight vehicle launch performance
 Procure IAL campaign 2 and additional UWL testing long lead support equipment and test articles
 Fabrication of flight test hardware for IAL and UWL
 Plan and Design missile storage and maintenance facilities
 Conduct Strategic Weapon Facility Nuclear Weapon Security requirement studies
 Develop Special Weapon Ordnance Publications
 Establish SLCM-N Nuclear Weapon Accountability Program at SWFs
 Develop and proof shipment, storage, handling and transfer special equipment and procedures for the SWFs
 Perform the following subsystem level reviews:

 Flight System Requirements and Functional Review

 Shipboard Systems:
 Responsible for lifecycle ownership of the SLCM-N nuclear fire control subsystem, submarine platform systems modifications and SLCM-N engagement and mission
 planning. Lifecycle ownership for nuclear fire control subsystems, submarine platform systems and engagement and mission planning include hardware and software
 systems engineering, trade studies, design, development, modeling, simulation, test, analysis, evaluation, reporting, verification, validation, acceptance, quality control,
 accreditation, certification, prototyping, installation, integration, production, operations, sustainment, maintenance, technical and training tools, equipment and products.
 Activities to be performed with mandatory funding include:
 Develop nuclear fire control subsystem, submarine platform systems and mission planning requirements
 Develop nuclear fire control subsystem prototypes
 Develop nuclear fire control subsystem and submarine platform systems artifacts in support of System Requirements Review
 Conduct Technology Maturation and Risk Reduction efforts, nuclear fire control subsystem prototypes, submarine platform systems and mission planning
 Establish subsystems agreements, assess and configure laboratories and facilities in support of prototype and subsystem interface verification
 Develop TEMPALT configuration design for launch platforms
 Conduct warhead demonstration and initial fire control prototype lab integration
 Conduct fire control Missile Processing Tool testing
 Develop subsystem interface verification criteria with SSN platform leads
 Develop SHIPALTs and draft engineering changes
 Leverage Limited Operational Capability (LOC) to support Shipboard integration and develop support equipment, procedures, trainers and facility activation

 Test & Evaluation:
 Plans and executes government test activities, providing support and oversight of Developmental Test and Evaluation (DT&E) activities, advocating for Test and
 Evaluation capabilities gaps, managing System Integration Labs, and collecting the test data necessary to perform data-derived verification and validation of the SLCM-
 N weapon system. This includes the planning, management and oversight of DT&E activities while maintaining insight into contractor test activities under the program,
 coordination and facilitation of Operational Test and Live Fire Test and Evaluation activities. Oversee the T&E activities of other participating government entities while
 ensuring the coordination and completion of the Test and Evaluation Master Plan in accordance with DoD guidance. Ensures adequate T&E resources and infrastructure
 are available to support the SLCM-N schedule. Ensures the conduct of SLCM-N cyber security testing. Activities to be performed with mandatory funding include:
 Conduct system integration lab study
 Conduct range capabilities assessment study
 Develop program required T&E documentation, including Test & Evaluation Master Plan (TEMP), Test strategy, schedule and program implementation
 Conduct planning, provisioning and execution of subsystem, and lower, Technology Maturation and Risk reduction developmental test and evaluations efforts
 Coordinate with OPTEVFOR (OT&E) for development of Integrated Evaluation Framework (IEF)
 Conduct planning for upgrades to range infrastructure to support future missile and capabilities testing at DOD test ranges
 Conduct launcher interface DT/validation
 Execute SLCM-N Weapon System Lab activation and integration testing

 (U)Evaluating alternative warhead options that meet military requirements while minimizing impact to the existing modernization Program of Record to the greatest
 extent possible.
 Warhead Systems will coordinate with the DOE to integrate the selected WH into the Navy delivery system, certify compatibility, and provide developmental hardware,
 support equipment (H, T and UC gear), operational procedures, and in-service support for the WH across all lifecycle activities per DODI 5030.55. Efforts will be
 coordinated with DOE/NNSA through the SLCM-N Project Officers Group and in accordance with FY2025 NDAA amended language. Activities to be performed with
 mandatory funding include:/Complete Phase 6.2/6.2A activities and begin Phase 6.3 activities for the SLCM-N warhead to include, but not limited to:
 Develop, assess, and test prototype components
 Conduct Warhead Subsystem Requirements Review
 Conduct Warhead Subsystem Conceptual Design Review
 Conduct manufacturing Process Prove-In and Engineering Evaluation to support Engineering Authorizations for product and process development
 Leverage Limited Operational Capability (LOC) to support warhead integration and surety strategies and develop support equipment, procedures, trainers, and facility
 activation
 Update Technology Readiness Levels, Manufacturing Readiness Levels and production cost estimates
 Develop Provisioning Plan for spare components
 Conduct Laboratory Task Group (LTG) and Joint Task Group (JTG) reviews to validate proposed procedures
 Develop the Stockpile Evaluation Program Plan and Joint DOD/DOE Nuclear Weapon Subsystem Test Plan
 Conduct independent peer reviews to validate technical and programmatic approaches with acceptable risk
 Conduct Warhead Subsystem Baseline Design Review
 Conduct Preliminary Design Review and Acceptance Group

 Limited Operational Capability:
 Responsible for the design, development, production, test, delivery and demonstration of a SLCM-N Limited Operational Capability per the FY2026 National Defense
 Authorization Act (NDAA). Activities to be performed with mandatory funding include:
 Develop detailed SOW and POA&M to execute Demo#1 flight test
 Develop SOW and POA&M to execute Demo#2 flight test
 Conduct Demo#1 flight test
 Support definition of power and data availability for WIU design
 Support definition of mechanical interface with minimal effect on flight performance
 Support development and testing of WH design
 Develop engineering concepts and perform scientific and engineering analyses and planning to achieve stated objectives
 Develop top level requirements, performance specifications, and mission requirements, and establish configuration functional
 baselines for the system
 Prepare Test and Evaluation Master Plans, procedures and test packages
 Conduct validation and verification of simulations, software, and hardware.

 Weapon Integration & Systems Engineering:
 Evaluates and establishes systems engineering policy for all phases of the Nuclear-Armed Sea-Launched Cruise Missile program, including overall safety, security, and
 program protection of the system. Manage and assess technical adequacy of SLCM-N weapon system (WS) planning and design. This includes defining SLCM-N WS
 technical milestones, establishing a standard process for component level reviews, and implementing weapon system-level engineering reviews. Establish system-level
 requirements, defining interfaces (coordination) between subsystems. Develop the overall SLCM-N WS architecture and maintain the flow down of model-based systems
 engineering as part of the overall systems and digital engineering strategy. Manage SLCM-N Risks, Issues and Opportunities, Decision Analysis, Digital Engineering,
 and Systems Engineering Control Board Processes. Implement and manage the SLCM-N Program Protection Plan, to include critical program information analysis
 and protection efforts. Oversee Safety, Surety, and Nuclear Weapon NW Security plans and processes. Manage all efforts associated with acquisition, documentation,
 contracts, financial management, logistics planning, fleet integration and Engineering Support Services/Professional Support Services (ESS/PSS) support. Activities to
 be performed with mandatory funding include:
 Provide technical program and project management of the SLCM-N program, including development and maintenance of task planning, expenditure monitoring/reporting
 Develop the Component Cost Estimate / Program Office Estimate, support preparation for Final Cost Review Board
 Develop the Acquisition Strategy and other documentation required for Gate 3 and Milestone A
 Develop documentation required for Milestone B
 Develop Integrated Master Plan (IMP) and Integrated Master Schedule
 Develop the Capabilities Development Document, Life Cycle Sustainment Plan and established the operational requirements, technical specifications and programmatic
 details of the SLCM-N program
 Coordinate with fleet stakeholders to develop requirements for tactical readiness, training, manpower, personnel, security, certification, documentation, publications,
 sustainment, maintenance, and employment
 Conduct Platform System Requirements Review and initiate Platform Preliminary Design Review
 Develop Verification & Validation Plan, Anti-Tamper Plan, and Modeling & Simulation Strategy
 Conduct safety, surety, and nuclear weapon security coordination
